Title: You, with a View
Author: Jessica  Joyce
My Review:
Fun, fast-paced, heartwarming, surprisingly-deep, and quick-witted, I loved the banter and serendipity of high school enemies-to-lovers Noelle and Theo reuniting for a family road trip to learn a secret (to Noelle) about her recently-deceased grandmother who'd dated Theo's grandfather.

It tackles serious subjects with wit and heart, adapted for the modern age of Tiktok. I loved the writing and how it takes place in the Bay Area!

Ultimately, I think this book is about the different stages and forms of grief, different perceptions of people (external and internal), and how failure is in the eye of the beholder (and how rejection is just redirection.)

Title: Imposter Syndrome and Other Confessions of Alejandra Kim
Author: Patricia  Park
My Review:
Quick read, but with beautiful, honest, modern writing, Patricia Park perfectly tackles what it means to not look like how people expect you to look because of your name, and the stereotypes and expectations that come with that.

Alejandra Kim isn't mixed-race, but she may as well be by the way people at her predominately-White private school treat her. Her family's Korean from South America, perfectly at the intersection of multiple boxes: yet people want to put her into one box.

Park perfectly satirizes and pokes fun at well-intentioned White people and how they view and treat multiculturalism and diversity. Must-read.

Title: Babel
Author: R.F. Kuang
My Review:
Beautifully-written. Artfully-articulated. Historically-researched and riveting. Love the syntax and the way it flows.

I think the main theme of the book questions and connects the relationship between languages, translation, and colonialism.

Can be slow to start and can get long, but it's a fun, interesting, deep, thought-provoking historical fiction novel that will make some readers uncomfortable and question what they thought they knew about words, languages, certain countries and colonialism, race, power, home, family, and gender.

Prior to reading this, I thought translation was fairly easy. Not that I could translate many things into or from other languages besides English, but I thought it meant finding an equivalent or equal in another language.

Kuang shows how great translation allows for innovation in the target language and delves into how the meanings of words change over time and how the roots can be connected and dissected and traced back to different meanings and histories.

Title: Not Here to Be Liked
Author: Michelle Quach
My Review:
Cute, fun, and lighthearted, "Not Here to Be Liked" tackled feminism in some ways that made me cringe at times, but was a satisfying read all the same. I appreciate the Asian diversity (Eliza's family is Chinese from Vietnam, the male protagonist is Japanese-White), her best friend is Black, and there's some LGBTQ representation as well.

I also appreciate the representation of Asian immigrant parents and how Eliza's mom looks down on her dad's restaurant job--this seems realistic in terms of how a marriage is portrayed as well as of how many Asians work in the industry!

It was fun to see Boba Bros (a play on Boba Guys?) and I felt that plotline could have been explored more.

There were some twists and turns, but ultimately I loved the portrayal of self-growth and collective growth as Eliza's classmates realized they were, indeed, misogynistic.

My Review:
Fun historical fiction YA book that tells a story of people we don’t often read or hear about: Chinese and Asian people in the American South.

They replaced slave labor after Reconstruction, but had trouble fitting in as in-between Black and White (they were more considered Black.)

The Downstairs Girl is a fun read filled with twists and turns and lots of wisdom and fortune-like Confucian-like phrases.

Title: Can't Even: How Millennials Became the Burnout Generation
Author: Anne Helen Petersen
My Review:
First review of 2021: This book was inspired/a continuation of a popular/viral/trendy Buzzfeed article by the same author. Clearly, the topic resonates with a lot of people.

The book is chock full of facts, quotes, and anecdotes, but moves quickly. It flows/reads well and is easy to read (probably because I'm a millennial and felt like I could relate to a lot of the stories.)

I like how the book touches on the root cause of burnout, looking at the history of labor and unions and our parents (boomers.) It touches on parenting, college, the over-working culture in Japan, and the dwindling middle class, providing an informative and fun look at the history, present, and future.

My Review:
The amount of research and detail in this book...Sarah Frier had to have put in WORK to get this information for this story that needed to be told. A must-read for tech enthusiasts and workers, by the end of the book, you will not view Facebook, Instagram, or Zuckerberg the same as how you did when you started.

It's also interesting to read to learn about startups, entrepreneurship, and funding. Instagram started out a lot differently than most companies in terms of organization and employees (though the founders were still privileged white bois from Stanford CS.)

Title: Legend (Legend, #1)
Author: Marie Lu
My Review: Similar to the hunger games yet in a league all it's own, Marie Lu successfully weaves a fast-paced, suspenseful, intense story filled with realistic, exciting, intelligent and fun characters with constant twists and turns. I know I usually can't put books down, but legend was especially different. I am now obsessed and loved Day and June, the main characters who are easy to relate to. With more mystery and suspense than most dystopian romances, (ie hunger games, divergent, matched, etc) this book will appeal to more types of people. Obviously, a must-read. Can't wait for the movie and sequel!
